  "articleSummary": "The article argues that the conventional advice to contribute to open source—finding \"Good First Issue\" labels—is often ineffective. Instead, it recommends leveraging problems you've already solved in your own projects, such as fixing outdated documentation or clarifying confusing API examples, since you're already fluent in the context. The tone is motivational and tutorial-like, using humor (e.g., the asterisk in the title hints at a disclaimer about luck and dedication) and recurring metaphors like \"drippin' in donations\" and \"rebasin' [Robb Report].\" The intended audience is developers who want to start contributing but feel stuck, with the core thesis that reflecting on your own struggles and sharing solutions publicly is the easiest path to impactful PRs.",
